'''Real utopian sociology''' is a [[sociology]] and type of emancipatory [[social science]] created and practiced by [[Erik Olin Wright]]. The seemingly contradictory term is literal, as the goal of real [[utopia]]n sociology is finding utopian projects in the world as it exists and systematically evaluating their potential to replace systems of domination, particularly capitalism.<ref name=":0">{{Cite web|url=https://www.ssc.wisc.edu/~wright/OVERVIEW.html|title=OVERVIEW|last=Wright|first=Erik|website=www.ssc.wisc.edu|access-date=2018-11-26}}</ref> Simply put, real utopian sociology is the scientific and pragmatic pursuit of studying utopian models for society as it could exist, and pathways to get there.<ref name=wash>{{cite news|title=Thinking Utopian: How about a universal basic income?|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/wonk/wp/2013/05/11/thinking-utopian-how-about-a-universal-basic-income/?utm_term=.039df752dace|author=Mike Konczal|date=11 May 2013|newspaper=The Washington Post}}</ref><ref name=opendem>{{cite web|url=https://www.opendemocracy.net/tni/sol-trumbo-vila-nick-buxton/atlas-of-real-utopias|title=An atlas of real utopias?|authors=Sol Trumbo Vila, Nick Buxton|publisher=OpenDemocracy|date=21 March 2018}}</ref>
Since 1991 Wright has organized a series of workshop conferences known as ''The Real Utopian Project'' that model the practice of real utopian sociology.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ssc.wisc.edu/~wright/RealUtopias.htm|title=RealUtopias|last=Wright|first=Erik Olin|website=www.ssc.wisc.edu|access-date=2018-11-26}}</ref> The conferences are sponsored by the A.E. Havens Center for Social Justice at the [[University of Wisconsin–Madison|University of Wisconsin-Madison]] and structured around “a provocative manuscript that lays out the basic outlines of a radical institutional proposal.”<ref name=":0"/> This manuscript is then sent to 15-20 scholars, who write essays on the topic. Prior to the conference these essays are circulated to all the conference participants and then each is discussed at the conference. Following the conference, participants have the opportunity to revise their work before it’s collectively published in Verso’s ''Real Utopias Project'' series; with the exception of papers from the first 1991 conference, which were not published as a series.<ref name=":0"/>
Past conference topics include: [[Basic income|Basic Income Grants]];<ref name=":0"/> Secondary Associations and Democratic Governance;<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://www.ssc.wisc.edu/~wright/Associations%20and%20Democracy%20--%20Real%20Utopias%20Project%20Volume%20I%20(1995).pdf|title=Associations and Democracy: The Real Utopias Project, Vol. 1|last=Center|first=A. E. Havens|last2=Project|first2=Real Utopias|last3=Cohen|first3=Joshua|last4=Hirst|first4=Paul Q.|last5=Immergut|first5=Ellen M.|date=1995|publisher=Verso|year=|isbn=9781859840481|location=London|pages=|language=English}}</ref> A Model for [[Market socialism|Market Socialism]], which was organized around the book, ''A Future for Socialism'', rather than a manuscript;<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://www.ssc.wisc.edu/~wright/Equal%20Shares%20--%20Real%20Utopias%20volume%20II%20(1996).pdf|title=Equal Shares: Making Market Socialism Work|last=|first=|date=|publisher=Verso|year=1996|isbn=9781859840535|editor-last=Wright|editor-first=Erik Olin|location=London|pages=|language=English}}</ref> Efficient Redistribution in Advanced Capitalism;<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://www.ssc.wisc.edu/~wright/Recasting%20Egalitarianism%20--%20Real%20Utopias%20Volume%20III%20(1998).pdf|title=Recasting Egalitarianism: New Rules for Communities, States and Markets|last=Brighouse|first=Harry|last2=Gintis|first2=Herbert|last3=|first3=|date=|publisher=Verso|year=1999|isbn=9781859842553|editor-last=Wright|editor-first=Erik Olin|location=London|pages=|language=English}}</ref> Deepening Democracy;<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://www.ssc.wisc.edu/~wright/Deepening.pdf|title=Deepening Democracy: Institutional Innovations in Empowered Participatory Governance|last=Abers|first=Rebecca Neaera|last2=Baiocchi|first2=Gianpaolo|last3=Cohen|first3=Joshua|date=2003|publisher=Verso|year=|isbn=9781859844663|editor-last=Fung|editor-first=Archon|location=London|pages=|language=English|editor-last2=Wright|editor-first2=Erik Olin}}</ref> Rethinking Redistribution;<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://www.ssc.wisc.edu/~wright/Redesigning%20Distribution%20v1.pdf|title=Redesigning Distribution: Basic Income and Stakeholder Grants as Cornerstones for an Egalitarian Capitalism|last=Ackerman|first=Bruce|last2=Alstott|first2=Anne|last3=Parijs|first3=Philippe van|date=2006-02-08|publisher=Verso|year=|isbn=9781844675173|location=London|pages=|language=English}}</ref> Pensions and the Control of Capital Accumulation;<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ssc.wisc.edu/~wright/RealUtopias.htm#Pensions%20and%20the%20Control%20of%20Capital%20Accumulation|title=RealUtopias|last=Wright|first=Erik Olin|website=www.ssc.wisc.edu|access-date=2018-11-26}}</ref> Institutions for Gender Egalitarianism: Creating the Conditions for Egalitarian Dual Earner/Dual Caregiver Families;<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://www.ssc.wisc.edu/~wright/Gender%20Equality%20--%20Real%20Utopias%20vol.%20VI%20(2009).pdf|title=Gender Equality: Transforming Family Divisions of Labor|last=Bergmann|first=Barbara|last2=Brenner|first2=Johanna|last3=Brighouse|first3=Harry|date=2009-08-03|publisher=Verso|year=|isbn=9781844673254|editor-last=Gornick|editor-first=Janet C.|location=London|pages=|language=English|editor-last2=Meyers|editor-first2=Marcia K.}}</ref> Legislature by Lot;<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.versobooks.com/books/2969-legislature-by-lot|title=Verso|website=www.versobooks.com|access-date=2018-11-26}}</ref> Pathways to a Cooperative Economy;<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ssc.wisc.edu/~wright/Cooperative-pathways.htm|title=Pathways to a cooperative Market|website=www.ssc.wisc.edu|access-date=2018-11-26}}</ref> and Democratizing Finance.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ssc.wisc.edu/~wright/Democratizing-Finance.htm|title=Pathways to a cooperative Market|website=www.ssc.wisc.edu|access-date=2018-11-26}}</ref>
